Banks are a major driver of climate disaster, as they provide the debt financing, without which the fossil fuel industry cannot fund its projects.
While banks publicly claim to be phasing out financing for fossil fuel extraction, financial reports show that they continue to pour billions into fossil fuel companies. For example, JP Morgan Chase has provided more than a quarter trillion dollars to the fossil fuel industry since the signing of the Paris Agreement.  Regulators of banks are responsible for protecting the stability of the economy and  therefore must require banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the damage banks cause through their deliberate financing of the companies causing climate disaster. 
